This document explores a dataset containing returns and attributes of different stores owned by an individual

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • There are 4,990 records of stores with 13 features (Item_ID, Store_ID, Item_Store_ID, Item_Weight, Item_Sugar_Content, Item_Visibility, Item_Type, Item_Price, Store_Start_Year, Store_Size, Store_Location_Type, Store_Type and Item_Store_Returns).
  • There are 8 Catgorical variables and 5 numerical variables. There are also aout 16% missing data Item_weight variable and 29% in the store_size.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • I'm interested in figuring what feature affects the return, does the size of the store, or its location type or even item type affect the return?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe the Store_Type, Store_Size, and Store_Location_Type, and Item_Store_Returns will give me insights on what store has the highest return. I would also be looking at the Item_Type and Item_Price

*goto top*

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • The range of values in the Item_store_return is large, so I used a log transform to view the data. I noticed majority of the return price falling below N10,000 and few above N10,000. Then a peak in frequency is seen at around N8,000.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • While investigating the Item weight, there were about 16% missing data which I filled with the mean of teh column. I noticed a normal distribution and a peak at 13kg as a result of the imputation.
  • I also noticed that there were three major Item types in the stores, Snack Foods, Fruits and Vegetables and Household goods. In general, it appears there were more edible items being stocked in the stores

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Item_Price and Item_Visibility have some correlation with the Item_Price_Returns. The higher the price of an item, the higher its return. I would've thought the visibility of the item would mean higher returns but the opposite is the case as the less visible items had higher returns than the more visible ones

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • Only Supermarket Type1 has all three sizes of store. The Grocery store type is a small sized store and Supermarket Type2 and 3 are medium sized stores. Interestingly, Supermarket Type3 has better returns than the rest on the average

Conclusions¶

The Item_Price, Item_Type, Store_Type and Store_Loaction_Type are features that affect the yield in return of the items.

In [ ]:
